goals.question: What is the overall trend of commits made to Github repositories between January 2015 and May 2015?
goals.visualization: Line chart of count vs time
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if the number of commits increased, decreased or remained constant over time.

goals.question: What is the distribution of the number of commits made to Github repositories?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the range of values for the number of commits made and how frequently they occur.

goals.question: What is the average number of commits made per day?
goals.visualization: Bar chart of count per day
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the average number of commits made per day and if there are any days with significantly higher or lower number of commits.

goals.question: What is the correlation between the number of commits made and the day of the week?
goals.visualization: Box plot of count vs day of the week
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if there is any correlation between the number of commits made and the day of the week. It will also help us identify any outliers.

goals.question: What is the distribution of the time of day when the commits were made?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the range of values for the time of day when the commits were made and how frequently they occur.

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    data['time'] = pd.to_datetime(data['time'], format='%Y/%m/%d %H:%M:%S', errors='ignore')
    plt.plot(data['time'], data['count'])
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    plt.title('What is the overall trend of commits made to Github repositories between January 2015 and May 2015?', wrap=True)
    return plt

chart = plot(data)

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    data['count'] = pd.to_numeric(data['count'])
    plt.hist(data['count'], bins=20)
    plt.xlabel('Number of Commits')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of the number of commits made to Github repositories?', wrap=True)
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.xticks(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    return plt

chart = plot(data)

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['time'] = pd.to_datetime(data['time'], format='%Y/%m/%d %H:%M:%S', errors='ignore')
    data = data.groupby(data['time'].dt.date).mean()
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    plt.bar(data.index, data['count'])
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    plt.title('What is the average number of commits made per day?', wrap=True)
    return plt

chart = plot(data)

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['time'] = pd.to_datetime(data['time'], format='%Y/%m/%d %H:%M:%S', errors='ignore')
    data['day_of_week'] = data['time'].dt.day_name()
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    ax = plt.boxplot(data.groupby('day_of_week')['count'].apply(list), showfliers=True, patch_artist=True)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    plt.title('What is the correlation between the number of commits made and the day of the week?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Day of the week')
    plt.ylabel('Number of commits')
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
